[28.329, "o", "\r\n\u001b[38;2;142;68;207m\u001b[1m  ━━ CLAUDE SYNTHESIS ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    # TH (Tyrosine Hydroxylase) — Expert Analysis\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    **Biological function.** TH catalyzes the rate-limiting step of catecholamine biosynthesis: conversion of L-tyrosine to L-DOPA using tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4), molecular oxygen, and iron as cofactors. The 497-aa canonical protein assembles as a homotetramer with an N-terminal regulatory domain (autoinhibitory, harboring Ser19/Ser31/Ser40 phosphorylation sites) and a C-terminal catalytic AAH (aromatic amino acid hydroxylase) domain. Activity is gated by phosphorylation (PKA, CaMKII, ERK1/2, PKC at Ser40 relieves catecholamine end-product feedback inhibition) and by 14-3-3 binding to pSer19. TH expression defines dopaminergic, noradrenergic, and adrenergic neurons — substantia nigra pars compacta (SNc), VTA, locus coeruleus, and adrenal chromaffin cells — making it the canonical marker for catecholaminergic identity.\r\n    **Transcript architecture.** The 14 annotated transcripts (8 protein-coding) reflect well-characterized alternative splicing in exon 1/2 producing human-specific TH1–TH4 isoforms tha"]
[0.000, "o", "t differ in the N-terminal regulatory region. These isoforms have distinct kinetics and phosphorylation responses; ignoring isoform-level resolution in bulk RNA-seq obscures biologically meaningful regulation. The chr11p15.5 location places TH adjacent to INS and IGF2 in an imprinted cluster — relevant for any locus-level expression or methylation work.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    **Disease associations.** Biallelic loss-of-function variants in TH cause **DOPA-responsive dystonia / Segawa-like syndrome and infantile parkinsonism (TH-deficiency, OMIM 605407)** — a treatable inborn error where early L-DOPA rescues motor phenotype; missing the diagnosis is a clinical failure because the therapeutic window matters. The promoter -824T variant and a microsatellite (TCAT)n polymorphism in intron 1 have reproducible associations with sympathetic tone, blood pressure variability, and pheochromocytoma risk. TH is the central node in **Parkinson's disease**: progressive SNc dopaminergic neuron loss is operationally defined by TH-immunoreactive cell loss, and TH gene therapy (AAV-TH ± AADC ± GCH1) is in active clinical development. TH-positive tumors include pheochromocytoma, paraganglioma, and neuroblastoma — where TH and DBH serve as both diagnostic IHC markers and minimal residual disease (MRD) targets in RT-PCR panels.\r\n    **Experimental recommendations.** (1) For neuronal identity "]
[0.000, "o", "assays, pair TH IHC with DAT/VMAT2 (dopaminergic) or DBH/PNMT (noradrenergic/adrenergic) — TH alone cannot distinguish subtype. (2) In iPSC-derived midbrain dopaminergic cultures, quantify TH+/MAP2+ co-expression and phospho-Ser40 TH as a functional readout, not just total TH. (3) For PD models, complement TH cell counts with stereology and unbiased dopaminergic markers (GIRK2 for A9, calbindin for A10) because TH downregulation precedes cell death and inflates apparent loss. (4) BH4 availability is rate-limiting in vivo — co-measure GCH1, QDPR, and sepiapterin reductase when interpreting TH activity. (5) For variant work, use isoform-aware quantification (Salmon/kallisto with the full GENCODE TH transcript set) rather than gene-level counts.\r\n    **Clinical translation.** Three actionable points: TH-deficiency should be on the differential for any infant with unexplained dystonia, hypotonia, or oculogyric crises — CSF HVA/HIAA ratio is the first-line biochemical test, and a trial of L-DOPA is both diag"]
[0.000, "o", "nostic and therapeutic. In PD, monitor the AAV2-GAD and AAV-AADC/TH/GCH1 trial readouts (Voyager, Axovant/Sio) for the dosing and serotype data relevant to any TH-directed gene therapy. In neuroblastoma, TH RT-PCR in bone marrow remains a sensitive MRD assay and outperforms morphology for low-burden disease detection.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n  \u001b[2m── 32.7s | Ensembl + UniProt + ClinVar + PubMed + Claude ──\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
